Horizons to East and South mostly dark.      Some, but not enough, stars from Magnitude 6 Chart were visible.
LocationComment: This is the Central Coast Astronomical Society (CCAS) star party site adjacent to the Santa Margarita Lake KOA Campground. Rural. SkyComment: Tonight the sky was remarkably clear and there were a lot of stars visible at the zenith and toward the east-northeast that aren't normally visible. The typical light pollution from Broussard and Lafayette was still present and still limited the view of the stars toward the south and west. The normal limiting magnitude from my house is usually about a 5.0. So, the extra 0.5 limiting magnitude was a real treat.
LocationComment: Suburban area of the Lafayette Metro area.  Large amount of light pollution from Lafayette and Broussard around horizon and above it. There are two street lights in front of my house, but behind it there are no street lights. Numerous houses have porch lights.

SkyComment: Apunté el SQM en dirección  Sureste y marcó 17.56  y también apunté en dirección Noroeste y marcó 13.43 .    Cúpula de la luz : luminarias dirigidas hacia abajo .      Yo vivo en Chillan, una  hermosa ciudad al  sur de Chile y al sur del mundo, estamos en  otoño, pero  el día que  hice mi observación no había vientos lluvia ni nubes.  El cielo estaba oscuro por lo que las estrellas  se veían  muy brillantes.  Venus se  veía  infinitamente bello y resplandeciente hacia el  noroeste de mi Ciudad. La  luna  no era visible desde acá, ya que estámos en luna nueva  pues el   sol  estaba alumbrando la cara  que no vemos de ella.    Soy Diego Alberto Torres Plaza curso octavo básico en la escuela Arturo Merino Benitez de Chillán , Chile .

SkyComment: The sky was clear.  While there was some increased sky glow in the southwest direction (in the direction of the main highway), it was slightly less than in previous years, mainly due to a number of local businesses turning off their outdoor signs after closing as well as the number of vacant stores on the highway.    The area around Leo was actually intermediate between the Magnitude 4 chart and the Magnitude 5 chart.  When factoring in stars that were flickering in and out of visibility, the view was closer to the Magnitude 5 chart.  Using my method of looking for the dimmest star definitely visible in the area and looking it up on Cartes du Ciel (a computer sky chart program) to get the magnitude, I arrived at an estimate of magnitude 4.6, which is about par for this location on a clear moonless night.  Had I observed from the backyard, subject to the direct glare of the floodlights I mentioned in the location comments, the magnitude figure might get to 4 if I was lucky.
LocationComment: The location is suburban.  There is a streetlight across the street in front of the house.  A neighbor to one side has a floodlight.  Another individual in the neighborhood has a bright floodlight mounted on the second floor of his oversized house.  There are two enormous trees in the back and side yards plus one monstrous tree in the front yard.  Sighting had to wait until Leo was in an area of sky unobstructed by trees.  Observed from the side of the detached garage which blocked the direct light of the floodlights and the house blocked the direct light of the streetlight.

SkyComment: Cielo parcialmente nublado en dirección Noreste, Norte y Noroeste. La ciudad desde mi patio se encuentra hacia el Norte, y las nubes en esa región se ven claramente de un color blanco mas iluminado que en el resto del cielo. Hacia el Sur las mismas son mas apagadas y menos iluminadas, haciéndose visible de tanto en tanto las estrellas propias de la Cruz del Sur. Hacia el Oeste, por arriba de los 40 grados esta totalmente despejado y Orion brilla en su esplendor, por debajo ya se notan las nubes de color gris acercarse rápidamente! En el Zenit, Sirio brilla sin ningún problema! Saludos

SkyComment: There was little clouds after the sun went down and it was a little bit cloudy at the skyline because of evaporated water from the sea nearby. However, we were lucky enough to observe all the beautiful things of the winter night and by naked eyes, we saw most of Northern stars. We could also obser the planets: Venus, Jupiter, Mars and Saturn. Later, we intended to observe M42 but a thin fog prevented us. Fortunately, we did wait till nearly 2:00 am and all the DSOs' treasures were revealed. Nothing more to expect for urban children like us!
LocationComment: Binh Chau - Phuoc Buu Natural Reservation located in Ba Ria - Vung Tau Province, Vietnam. There was no lights or bulbs except of few lights from our camp. There also was a basin at the heart of the reservation, an interesting place for lying down and observe. It is wide enough to make the trees, which take about 10 degree in the skyline, become shorter. That's it, a perfect stargazing destination.

SkyComment: Sky was free of any visible cloud cover, and the amount of visible stars seemed better than most nights. Typical light haze comes from further north (when facing the airport several miles away), but Orion was far enough West at the time to still see many of the fainter stars--and the moon wasn't out at the time to disrupt visibility. I'd say the sky was between Mag 4 and Mag 5--I counted a total of 18 stars within the Orion constellation.

SkyComment: The clouds seem to blend into the indigo night sky. Even if only slightly dimmer, the stars tonight are still visible. The reddish star, the brightest star of the night, is still the quite prominent. It would seem that in order from nearest to farthest, the stars go from more dim to less dim as compared to the previous nights. The star that used to be nearest the reddish star is not gone dave for a speck of light color left. There is a slight breeze that seems to be moving towards the north. Besides the reddish star, I clearly see three stars now. The star farthest from the reddish star is rather dim tonight as well.

SkyComment: The sky was fairly hazy in the east with some clouds moving across my line of vision every few minutes. The color of the sky was a dark purple while I was observing, which made the stars stand out more. The constellation Orion was especially bright, and there were a few dimmer surrounding stars. However, due to the nearby lights it was difficult to see very many.
LocationComment: Suburban college town with a lot of lights (for campus safety purposes). At least one large lamppost every fifteen feet, with other sources of light emitting from residence hall windows and the hotel next door. Trees here are very spread out and generally similar in height and width for aesthetic purposes, with a small thicket of leafy ones to separate the campus buildings from the privately owned ones. The buildings are plentiful but low to the ground; most are no more than four or five floors, with the exception being two apartment towers which emit more light from a radio transmitter on the roof. There is a main road nearby so the area has a fair amount of car traffic, and the headlights passing by generate another consistent source of light.

SkyComment: The sky had a general light haze over part of the sky. There were not many full clouds, but the haze definitely served as an impediment to the visibility of stars. If I changed the direction of where I was facing then I could see different levels of visibility. It is unfortunate that there was a haze covering part of the sky because it made it a lot difficult to enjoy all of the different constellations that are visible in good conditions and with a location with minimal light and high altitude.
LocationComment: I was in the backyard of my house at 108 Wilbur Street. There is an apartment complex in behind my backyard that has parking lots lights on at all hours of the night. I could also see some light from different houses on Cleveland Avenue. The buildings surround me were not very high so they did not get in the way of my view of the sky. I think that there definitely was light pollution in the region because there are so many houses in my region that have different levels of lights on. SkyComment: I observed the sky from my girlfriend's house in Harford County, Maryland. The latitude is 39.656914 and the longitude is -76.530059 at the exact location at which I observed. The night was perfectly clear. Harford County is out in the country so there is very little light pollution. I can say that I have never seen so many stars in the sky in my life. It was a surreal experience. I am from a town similar to Newark, so I have never really seen the actual night sky without the effects of light pollution. The magnitude at this location must have been around 1 or 2, I cannot imagine the night sky being much more clear. I just thought about how in early civilizations there was no real light pollution like there is today, so the stars must have amazed those people. It used to be odd to think that people got so much use from the stars in the old days because I have not (due to light pollution). But after seeing them, I wish that there was less pollution because seeing n illuminated night sky is a joy that everyone should have, every night.   The night sky itself was unbelievable. I was able to see the night sky filled with stars. The backdrop was so dark that each star light up like a pinpoint of intense light. The color was invasive. Points of light lit up everywhere and created an intricate pattern across the sky. It was easy to identify constellations such as Orion. It was also easy to create shapes in my own mind, similar to how children make shapes out of the clouds. The night sky was an amazing thing to see. Overall, it was a great experience to see a night sky without the effects of light pollution. I hope to see more skies like this, so hopefully something can be done about light pollution to encourage viewing the night sky.

It was on a golf course that was pretty far out of the way of everything, so it was pretty dark. There were a couple of buildings with lights really far in the distance, but I don't think they affected our measurements too much. However, there was a soccer game going on nearby, and the floodlights lit up the sky quite a bit and probably screwed up our measurements a bit.  If the game hadn't been going on we probably would have been able to see even more.

SkyComment: Looking for Leo was very difficult.  Although the sky was clear and barely clouded, I am not too familiar with Leo. I had to keep referring to the instruction online to find Leo. I looked for the North Start first, then work my way south to find Leo. Once I figured out Leo’s tail, it was easier to spot him when I looked away. The lights around the development had no influence on my ability to see the stars. There is definitely a large contrast between the points of the light and the darkness around. I noticed that on campus, I do not really see the brightness of the stars because of the lights coming out of the dorms. However, when seeing the starts outside the parking with few lighting, I was able to notice the brightness of the starts even more. Although the sky was clear, Leo was harder to find the Orion. Leo does not have a distinct figure like Orion. I found Orion easier to find because of the belt which is unique. I definitely appreciate the sky night better after this project.
LocationComment: Suburban area. Right outside the parking lot of a townhouse development. No streetlights, no porch lights, no snow cover. There were only two very dim tan color light-polls at the right end and left end of the street. There were also small trees in the parking lot. The biggest one was behind me so it did not block my view. From where I was standing, I had a good view of the night sky. No streets blocking or lights distracting my view. In conclusion, location was fairly good and appropriate to look at the night sky

SkyComment: The sky was slightly cloudy with barely any haze. I chose magnitude 1 because I can see the starts clearly. The starts were a bright white which allowed me to enjoy the view even more. Since the sky was clear, I was able to spot Orion’s belt quickly. When facing south, I spotted Orion on my right (southwest). I am not completely familiar with Orion’s shape so I choose to spot the belt first and work my way to figure out Orion’s shape. The lights around the development had no influence on my ability to see the stars. There is definitely a large contrast between the points of the light and the darkness around. I noticed that on campus, I do not really see the brightness of the stars because of the lights coming out of the dorms. However, when seeing the starts outside the parking with few lighting, I was able to notice the brightness of the starts even more.
LocationComment: Suburban area. Right outside the parking lot of a townhouse development. No streetlights, no porch lights, no snow cover. There were only two very dim tan color light-polls at the right end and left end of the street. There were also small trees in the parking lot. The biggest one was behind me so it did not block my view. From where I was standing, I had a good view of the night sky. No streets blocking or lights distracting my view. In conclusion, location was fairly good and appropriate to look at the night sky

SkyComment: The sky is an indigo color today. There are pinkish clouds tonight. The stars tonight are more noticeable. Besides the reddish star, I see five other stars. Four of them are blue and most prominent. The star nearest to the reddish star, the more noticeable star of the nigh every night, is very dim. It's luminosity is about the same as yesterday: I have to squint a bit to be sure it is actually there. I also think that I see stars surrounding the stars farthest away from the reddish star. These stars are more to the south. In between the group of stars and the reddish star are two of the brightest stars tonight. The clouds move northward.
LocationComment: Between two apartment buildings. I'm on the third floor of a 7 floor apartment building that's parallel to a 6 floor building. It continues to be parallel until a block. There is a street light too my far right. There is not enough light for the observation to be hindered. The only noticeable lights are from behind me, my apartment, and from below. I live in a suburban place. The other side of the boulevard is full of stores. It is quiet here. There are no birds.

SkyComment: There was some haze on the horizon, but it, as well as the very few stratus clouds we saw, were located very close to the ground. The sky itself was very clear directly above me - looking at the stars was great, because the sky surrounding the stars was so clear.    It was a little difficult to find Leo because there were less stars surrounding the bright stars that help you find the constellation. However, once I pinpointed some of the brighter stars, I was able to see the rest of the constellation, though much of it was faint.
LocationComment: The area is a state park, so it is a very open space in and of itself, located in a more rural area. However, it is immediately off of Rt. 896, a rather large highway, so there were numerous cars which provided light but no street lights. Other than the car lights and a few dispersed house lights, there were no lights in the surrounding area. There were some trees surrounding the interspersed houses (they were very spaced out), as well as on the outskirts of the park. The area was mainly very empty, though.

SkyComment: The sky is partially cloudy with some haze. The stars I can see appear silvery. Beyond what I know to be Orion's belt, I cannot notice any symmetry or relative shape.

SkyComment: The sky was very clear tonight and I could see a good amount of stars. Tonight was great observing conditions as major stars and constellations were clearly visible. I was able to identify Venus, Jupiter, Mars and all stars within Orion, Leo, and the big and little dippers. There was some haze and some stratus clouds dispersed on the lower level of the sky towards the ground, however, they did not affect the visibility of the stars that are higher in the sky.
LocationComment: I observed the night sky at Nichol Park on New London Road in Landenberg, Pennsylvania. This is a very rural area. The park is a large open field that is surrounded by trees. There are not many structures around it, however, there were a few houses interspersed on the road on the side of the park. It was very dark which really helped to be able to see the stars and planets in the sky. The only light sources in the vicinity of the area where we observed the sky was the headlights from the cars driving by on the road next to the park. There were no street lights or light posts at the park, so besides from the cars driving by, it was very dark.

Outdoor porchlights on about a dozen vacation homes within 200 meters, some bare bulbs, some with ineffective shading.  I'm viewing from a patio with high wals on east, south, and west sides that block some of the worst porchlights. Home to the west on Lana lane has bright string of Christmas lights still decorating a tall cardon cactus. For such tiny lights they throw off a lot of light into the sky. From the roof of my house I cannot view gthe sky to the south because one small  compact florescent light shines brightly under a porch overhang. I see fewer stars in Orion tonight, probably due to haze.  Ten years ago this was easily a magnitude 6 location.

SkyComment: The sky is a more solid blue. It is less light and less purple. The star nearest to the reddish star of Orion is less lighter than the previous night; I can hardly see it. The star farthest away from the reddish star is the brightest. Its light is more evidently inconsistent. Its luminosity almost rivals that of the red star. The star in between the two blue stars (the two stars aside from the reddish one) has a luminosity between the one nearest and farthest away from the reddish star. The star to my far right, right to the brightest star, right to the reddish star, is brighter than usual. It is towards southeast.

The sky is a hazy purple, but there are no clouds tonight. I see three prominent stars above me. There are more to the opposite building.  There is one unblinking reddish tinted star to my left, more to the elementary school east. It shines more brightly than the three stars in front. If I looked directly up from my fire escape, I see three more stars, all further apart than the first three stars that I saw. If I squinted, I saw a trail of stars to my front right. They are very, very dim. I could be mistaken. I believe I am looking at Orion. gain, if I squinted, I think I see some stars surrounding one of the three prominent stars. This star is the farthest away from the big, reddish star from my left.

My eyesight is 20/10 in both eyes and for me, visibility was better than I indicated but is very accurately assessed: most other normally-sighted people agree with my assessment as indicated.    There was a very strong wind blowing and those people running asteroid tracking programs indicated that the bloom was about the worst they've seen in a  while.  It was just slightly hazy, with less than one-tenth cloud cover of stratiform clouds.  I believe that dust was a factor to be dealt with.  Estimated wind strength was 25-35 knots with peak gusts up to 50 knots.    (I am a retired  airline pilot of 42 years experience, and was a certified weather observer for NOAA in Fort Yukon, AK  in 1977.)
LocationComment: N37 deg 49 min 09 sec  W122 deg 10 min 54 sec    Chabot  Space and Science Center,  Oakland, CA. USA    Observation made atop a forested hill 1500 feet above the East Bay of Oakland CA on the observation deck of a science center.  The depicted location in Modesto, CA is where I am making this report, not where I made the observation.

SkyComment: I can send an e-mail photo showing the steep gradient in light pollution from the conurbation.  No clouds.  Transparency good. Sirius may be in the beam and may be the cause of the  0.22 magnitude brighter reading than obtained in January (or that may be caused by the tourist peak in February - section 2)

SkyComment: Strong gradient in light pollution, high to West (few stars visible over Coquimbo and La Serena) low to East (Milky Way visible).  No clouds, fog or obvious haze.  My eyes lose about a magnitude compared with average vision, so I prefer to trust the SQM reading.  I am providing here a mean of several measures taken with a narrow-FOV SQM #2791, i.e. 19.89 mag.   (A wide-band SQM # 1277 takes in more pollution to the West and more Milky Way to the East - and gave readings about a third of a magnitude brighter i.e. ~19.56 mag).  No obvious glow above the Coquimbo stadium (clear air).
LocationComment: Outer suburban garden east of La Serena-Coquimbo conurbation (which now has about 439,230 inhabitants and is growing at a rate of 32% per decade).  No snow (southern summer).  No street lights or other light sources in SQM beam.  White lights are on at the the Coquimbo football stadium about 10km? to the SW.

SkyComment: Strong gradient in light pollution, high to West (few stars visible over Coquimbo and La Serena), low to East (Milky way visible).  No clouds, fog or obvious haze.     Note: I am 25% short of completing my 70th orbit around the sun, so my eyes lose about a magnitude compared with average vision.  I prefer you use my SQM measures for Globe at Night.  I am providing here a mean of measures taken with a narrow-band SQM #2791 namely 19.92 magnitudes.  The reading with  wide beam #1277 was 19.34 (sees more of the pollution).

LocationComment: Suburban, 4 miles from Springfield, Illinois-a city of more than 100,000. The observation location is the rear of a split level home which obscures much of the light coming from Springfield. One neighbor's porch visible and obstructive. Light halo from Springfield is not visible on this side of the apex.  Light sources visible from location include interior lights from nearby residences, 1 street light--obscured by trees. Structures include a two car garage, and nearby homes, but the observation point is high enough that structures only obscure view of horizon and the lowest stars. There are trees present to the south, but at this point in the year, they do little to obscure the view. A little snow cover, but much has melted and reflected light is minimal. No moon. All in all, after allowing a few minutes for the eye to adjust, one can see satellites with relative ease.
